{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bbf30308-f72c-4579-923e-4a50855127e1","content":"\n\n**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after a SDK update, since workloads need to be re-aligned to the new SDK version.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions of workloads already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't fetch newer versions.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → workloads need new versions → `dotnet workload update`. If the build still fails after that, a `dotnet workload repair` can rule out a corrupted install.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"864f108e-309d-4de6-a004-f9129ad156be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.","outputTokens":215},"id":"e6878329-b525-4726-b293-840d715cefa6","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:45.267Z","parentId":"f56d6476-20fe-4491-87c7-4318bc60e596"}
